<DOC><DOCNO> AP890916-0116 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 1724EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-16 0406</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0417</SECOND><HEAD>Rain and Storms Affecting Wide Areas</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A hurricane neared the Caribbean and a tropical depression spreadrain over the Southwest on Saturday, and rain fell across theMidwest and much of the East.   Hurricane Hugo headed for the Leeward Islands and hurricanewarnings were posted for Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands.Its highest sustained wind speed was about 140 mph, with strongergusts.   Tropical depression Octave spread moist air over the Southwest.Light rain caused slippery streets in the Los Angeles basin and fellfrom San Diego to Santa Barbara. Thunderstorms over the DiabloMountains and Livermore Valley dropped about half an inch of rainnear Livermore, Calif.   Showers and thunderstorms also extended over western Arizona.   Showers and thunderstorms also extended over southern LowerMichigan, Indiana, northern Ohio, Kentucky, West Virginia, westernNew York state, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Virginia, Maryland, NorthCarolina, eastern South Carolina, the Georgia coast and the Floridacoast.   A tornado was reported on the ground in North Carolina's LenoirCounty on Saturday afternoon.   Almost 4 inches of rain fell at Fayetteville, N.C., in two hourslate Friday and more rain fell overnight, causing flooding in whichtwo children drowned.   In parts of West Virginia, creeks were swollen by more than 3inches of rain Saturday, forcing some families to leave their homesand drowning two people, authorities said.   Elsewhere, showers were scattered over western Washington state.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53 atBremerton and Everett, Wash., to 100 at Phoenix. Saturday's low forthe Lower 48 states was 19 at Gunnison, Colo.   For Sunday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from NewEngland and New York state across eastern South Carolina, easternGeorgia and the Florida Peninsula, as well as from the Pacific Coastacross Montana, western Wyoming, Utah and Nevada.   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted over New England and NewJersey across the Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley and the Appalachians,from Montana, Idaho, western Utah and northern Arizona across thenorthern two-thirds of the Pacific Coast, and along the southerncoast of California; near 90 over much of Florida, much of Texas,western Oklahoma and western sections of the central Plains; in the90s over North Dakota and western South Dakota, as well as fromsouthern Arizona through the desert Southwest; and generally in the80s over the remainder of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>